GKE Network Policy — controlling pod-to-pod traffic

Objective
Apply a Network Policy to block frontend from reaching backend;
prove it works before and after the policy is applied

Key Concepts
- By default all pods in a GKE cluster can talk to each other freely
- Network Policy = firewall rules for pod-to-pod traffic inside a cluster
- Policies use labels to select pods — not names or IPs
- Pod names change on restart; labels stay consistent
- ingress: [] = deny all inbound traffic to selected pods
- --enable-network-policy must be set at cluster creation — cannot add after
- Without it, Network Policies are created but completely ignored
- kubectl exec POD -- COMMAND = run a command inside a running pod
- curl exit code 28 = connection timed out = traffic blocked

Practical Work Completed
- Created cluster with --enable-network-policy flag
- Deployed frontend and backend pods with labels
- Proved free communication before policy (nginx page returned)
- Created and applied Network Policy with ingress: []
- Proved policy blocked traffic (curl exit code 28 = timeout)
- Cleaned up: pods and cluster deleted

Confusions / Fixes
- Yesterday's lab failed because --enable-network-policy was missing
- Today it worked correctly with the flag included

Mental Model
Network Policy = pod-level firewall
Labels = how you identify which pods the policy applies to
ingress: [] = no one can send traffic to these pods
--enable-network-policy = the switch that makes enforcement real

Plain English Summary
Ssuccessfully proved Network Policy works when the cluster is created
correctly. Before the policy — frontend reached backend freely. After applying
the policy — connection timed out. The key lesson from this week: two things
that look like the same problem (403 errors) have different causes —
Workload Identity failure vs missing IAM role on the resource. 
